  "body": "### Component\r\n\r\nFoundryup\r\n\r\n### Have you ensured that all of these are up to date?\r\n\r\n- [X] Foundry\r\n- [X] Foundryup\r\n\r\n### What version of Foundry are you on?\r\n\r\nforge 0.2.0 (16b4ef6 2022-07-13T00:05:41.265337096Z)\r\n\r\n### What command(s) is the bug in?\r\n\r\n`foundryup`\r\n\r\n### Operating System\r\n\r\nLinux\r\n\r\n### Describe the bug\r\n\r\nI am trying to run `foundryup` in a `Dockerfile` so I can test a tool I'm integrating with it on CI.\r\n\r\nThis is what I have:\r\n\r\n```\r\nUSER user:user\r\nWORKDIR /home/user\r\n\r\nRUN curl -L https://foundry.paradigm.xyz | bash && foundryup --version nightly-16b4ef693624368e02e3501dd137214faf9bbe76 \r\nENV PATH=/home/user/.foundry/bin:$PATH\r\n```\r\n\r\nThere are 2 problems:\r\n\r\n- [ ] `foundryup` cannot detect what shell is running in the Dockerfile (image below), and so exits with non-zero exit-code. So I have to add an `_ || true` to the `RUN` line which means I'll be ignoring real errors (I'm setting up the environment on the next line anyway).\r\n- [ ] Not many versions of `foundry` are being tagged, which means that pegging a specific version on CI will be difficult, which makes our development process more painful.\r\n\r\n![Screenshot from 2022-07-13 20-07-42](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/12721972/178882538-8755b5a8-a8a8-48f6-977d-6ef77757ec37.png)\r\n",
